<h4 id="how-did-our-work-move-forwards">How did our work move forwards?</h4>

<p>Giving room to â€“ and sometimes doing the work to make room for â€“ the team, as a group or individuals, to go and do their thing is becoming more habitual. I posed the question a few weeks back â€œWhy is it we give more value to meetings other people put in our calendar than work for our sprint goals? What if we treated work for sprint goals like meetings. Get that work into calendars first, and fit the other stuff around that.â€ Environment is another thing: If the open office provides difficulties for you to do whatâ€™s the most important thing, go somewhere else that is more suitable. I completely trust the researchers, designers, business analysts, product owners, and delivery managers I closely work with. Some of them I work with more closely than others (I am highly reluctant to say â€œthe UCD teamâ€, because a team within a team is uurrrr), but making sure they have the best conditions to do what they come to work to do is one of my regular goals.</p>

<p>We spent some time this sprint putting down some of the structure around â€œdesigningâ€ every sprint. There is nothing wrong with formalising your designing process (as long as it is just enough process), as it helps you knowing what you are focused on and helps everyone else know what is going on. Take prioritised problems into a sprint, hypothesise, design, get a response to that, analyse the research, how does that effect our work (move along our understanding? close issues? raise more issues?). There was also some ~sterling~ awesome work from user researcher Lisa to move the â€œUR planâ€ into being more a â€œplan for designingâ€, which a lot more of the team can own, contribute to and refer to. It should help the product owners make decisions too. Referring to the plan and updating the plan will at least be part of our sprint cycle. Also documenting design decisions doesnâ€™t happen enough. I donâ€™t want us to not do that as habit. This will help.</p>

<p>The things we take into sprint need to be tighter as well in focus and size, so we make steadier progress and the wider team can benefit by carrying forward these smaller chunks of work. To help frame this I used â€œIf we had to stop working on the project at the end of the sprint something could still be made and people would understand where we got to: What is good and what needs more design workâ€. This folds back to documenting enough, but just enough.</p>

<p>Monday I spent time with the service team at their base. I am trying to get some solidity around the work flow â€“ basically surfacing the touch points with DWP a claimant could make and the tools (conversations, forms, guides, digital products and so on) we use as people working for the department â€“ against a limited number of scenarios (which arenâ€™t â€œhappyâ€ paths â€“ and I am acutely aware â€œhappyâ€ is rarely the right word to use when navigating people through social care). The service team are collaborating in designing the process so everything I offered up at the start has been â€œhereâ€™s our educated guesses, letâ€™s use our experience and skills to make it betterâ€. Itâ€™s rewarding to see that work progress, to see stuff scrutinised, moved about, refined. I think too much we overlook the value of having the people doing the work designing what theyâ€™ll be doing daily â€“ it brings constructive critical thinking in sooner, prolongs that mindset as the process is being used, makes changing stuff later more considered and possible, and thereâ€™s something in there about training (which I wonâ€™t go into). Having the teamâ€™s understanding and being comfortable with what we and they are doing is a goal. We recognise things that are uncomfortable? Get those into some shape where there is a greater degree of comfort. It might be continually uncomfortable for me as a designer, but working with the work flow we are designing shouldnâ€™t be uncomfortable for those using it.</p>

<p>Mondayâ€™s work set up another session with the service team on Thursday, led by Jo (one of the user researchers I work with) and Sam (our interaction designer), and with a couple of business analysts (David and Kirsty) in attendance. We wanted to think through openly â€œAs a service team if we were â€˜record thingsâ€™ along the work flow what would help us and the claimant reach their goal?â€</p>

<p>Had a few chats and thinks about a particular part of the journey where a digital tool is very useful. I am thinking of taking on some interaction design work in the coming week to help me get under the skin of that tool (and the problems around it).</p>

<p>Had a helpful conversation about how we â€œframeâ€ our work. The word â€œpilotâ€ has been used. Every â€œpilotâ€ I have worked on has had some degree of difference in definition. â€œWe are doing a pilotâ€ never gets across the intention of the work. Some of us are finding framing the work we are doing around â€œalphaâ€ and â€œbetaâ€ against the existing gov service manual a lot more useful: clearer and also leaning a standard that is already established. â€œAt the moment we are doing some deeper discovering and testing some design thoughts so we are in alpha.â€ â€œBy this date we intend to be doing something with a small group of users, so a betaâ€. Context.</p>

<p>I talked to a couple of bits of DWP that want to be involved, that have been kept at armsâ€˜ length. Itâ€™s not about about saying no, itâ€™s been about saying â€œwe want you to be involved but can you let us get our heads straight before we get you involvedâ€. Some of those times are now.</p>

<p>Friday, had a lovely chat about a ministerial task force meeting in a month or so. I came away chipper that other people are interested in accessibility as a habit of designing not as a bolt on.</p>

